  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 17.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "A great pit;",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Hebrew, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "the great pit",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; as though there was some great hollow or well known depression in the wood, into which they cast Absalom's dead body, and raised a cairn over it. Such cairns were used as memorials of any event deemed worthy of lasting remembrance, but the similar cairn piled over the dead body of Achan (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 7:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") makes it probable that the act was also intended as a sign of condemnation of Absalom's conduct. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "All Israel fled every one to his tent.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The Israelites were still a pastoral people, with tents for their abodes, though houses were gradually taking their place. The cry, \"To your tents, O Israel!\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 12:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), meant, \"Go away to your homes!\" and not \"Gather for war!\" It is remarkable how constantly Absalom's followers are described as \"Israel\" while the loyal men are \"David's  servants.\" Absalom's was evidently the popular cause, and, besides Uriah's murder, there must have been political reasons for discontent at work to make David's government so distasteful. 2 Samuel 18:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "But Absalom they cast into a great pit in the wood, and threw up over him a very large heap of stones, as an ignominious monument, like those thrown up over Achan (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 7:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") and the king of Air (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 8:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). This was the end of Absalom and his rebellion. \"All Israel (that had crowded round him) had fled, every one to his tent\" (i.e., home: see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 16:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]